\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 STATE OF ARIZONA, ET AL., PETITIONERS, v. UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, RESPONDENT.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 No. \cf17 \b \i0 \ul0 11-182\cf \b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 2011 U.S. Briefs 182; 2012 U.S. S. Ct. Briefs LEXIS 1245
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 March 26, 2012
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 On Writ of Certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \qc \li1200\ri1200 \sb0 \fi0 Amicus Brief
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 COUNSEL: \b0 \i0 \ul0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**1]\b0 \i0 \ul0   WADE HENDERSON, LISA BORNSTEIN, THE LEADERSHIP CONFERENCE ON CIVIL AND HUMAN RIGHTS, Washington. DC, NANCY MORAWETA, Counsel of Record, WASHINGTON SQUARE LEGAL SERVICES. INC., New York, NY, Counsel for Amici Curiae.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*i]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 INTERESTS: \b0 \i0 \ul0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*1]\b0 \i0 \ul0   STATEMENT OF INTEREST
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights is a diverse coalition of more than 200 national organizations charged with promoting and protecting the rights of all persons in the United States. \b0 \i \ul0 Amici curiae\b0 \i0 \ul0  are civil rights, faith, and community organizations whose constituents will suffer the harmful effects of S.B. 1070 and copycat legislation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 By pursuing "attrition through enforcement," states that enact these laws announce to immigrants and people of color that they are not welcome and will be subjected to constant scrutiny--as well as to the demeaning experience of criminal arrest and detention. These policies not only are unjust; they also create criminal consequences that inherently conflict with congressional policy.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 For these reasons, \b0 \i \ul0 amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  urge affirmance of the injunction. A full list of \b0 \i \ul0 amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  are appended after the conclusion of this brief. n1
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n1 \b0 \i \ul0 Amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  state that no counsel for a party authored any part of this brief, and no person or entity other than \b0 \i \ul0 amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  and their counsel made a monetary contribution to the preparation or submission of this brief. Both Petitioners and Respondent have lodged letters of blanket consent to the filing \b0 \i \ul0 of amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  briefs.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 TITLE: \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b \i0 \ul0 BRIEF FOR THE LEADERSHIP CONFERENCE ON CIVIL AND HUMAN RIGHTS, SOUTHERN POVERTY LAW CENTER, LEAGUE OF UNITED LATIN AMERICAN CITIZENS, NATIONAL ASIAN PACIFIC AMERICAN BAR ASSOCIATION, NATIONAL CONGRESS OF AMERICAN INDIANS, LEGAL MOMENTUM, LAMBDA LEGAL DEFENSE AND EDUCATION FUND, AFRICAN AMERICAN MINISTERS IN ACTION, AMERICAN JEWISH COMMITTEE, LEADERSHIP CONFERENCE OF WOMEN RELIGIOUS, AND OTHER CIVIL RIGHTS, FAITH, AND COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS AS AMICI CURIAE IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENT\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*2]\b0 \i0 \ul0   SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 If the enjoined provisions of S.B. 1070 are allowed to go into effect, they will work harms on individuals who would not suffer such harms under the federal immigration scheme. Although purportedly targeting "unlawfully present" immigrants, S.B. 1070 will dramatically harm the lives of U.S. citizens, Lawful Permanent Residents ("LPRs"), and other individuals across a spectrum of immigration statuses--such as asylum seekers and victims of violent crimes--in ways that run counter to the federal immigration scheme.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 S.B. 1070 endangers a broad swath of people in large part because it misapprehends \b \i0 \ul0 [**10]\b0 \i0 \ul0   federal immigration law. Underlying S.B. 1070 are two fallacies. The first is that each person fits into one of two categories--those who are "lawfully present" and those who are not. The second is that Arizona law enforcement officers can readily distinguish between these categories by simply reviewing a certain set of federally mandated documents, or by calling the federal government on the telephone.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In reality, even U.S. citizens often will not be readily identifiable; and where non-citizens are concerned, determining a person's immigration status requires a nuanced legal inquiry, which cannot be performed by police on the beat. Moreover, many non-citizens whom the federal government permits to be in this country will lack documentary proof of that permission.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 On top of these erroneous premises, S.B. 1070 layers a system of criminal consequences that run roughshod over the critical distinctions between  \b \i0 \ul0 [*3]\b0 \i0 \ul0   criminal law and civil immigration law. For example. Section 3 will subject to arrest and prosecution many thousands of people who, under the federal scheme, are not criminally liable. And Section 6 superimposes Arizona officers' \b0 \i \ul0 state criminal\b0 \i0 \ul0  warrantless arrest \b \i0 \ul0 [**11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   authority onto \b0 \i \ul0 federal civil\b0 \i0 \ul0  immigration enforcement. Even federal officers are generally not authorized to make warrantless arrests.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 S.B. 1070 has spawned a slew of copycat laws in other states seeking "attrition through enforcement." n2 The Court's decision in this case will thus shape the fates of people nationwide. In states such as Utah, Indiana, Georgia, Alabama, and South Carolina, n3 people of color will be subjected to constant scrutiny regarding their immigration status--and to the demeaning experience of criminal arrest and detention. S.B. 1070 and its copycats thus divide our nation between those regions where people of all ethnicities can freely travel, live, and work--and those where they cannot.
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n2 2010 Ariz. Legis. Serv. Ch. 113.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 n3 Petition for Writ of Certiorari at 23.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In the face of S.B. 1070's plain language, Petitioners ask the Court to identify some narrow reading of the statute, in the hope that the law might survive this facial challenge. The Court should not strain to identify such a legal fiction. The stated motives of its proponents, the stated understandings of its would-be enforcers, and real-world evidence all belie Petitioners'  \b \i0 \ul0 [**12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   theoretical argument that S.B. 1070 can be implemented in a manner consistent with the Constitution.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*4]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 ARGUMENT\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 I. THOUGH PURPORTEDLY TARGETED AT "UNLAWFUL PRESENCE," S.B. 1070 WILL HARM U.S. CITIZENS.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A crucial flaw of S.B. 1070 is the assumption that officers can determine "lawful presence" on the spot, simply by looking at a person's documents or by placing a phone call to the federal government. This "papers please" approach is one not generally pursued by federal agents, and is unworkable for the reasons discussed herein. Chief among them is the fact that U.S. citizens comprise the largest group of undocumented people in the United States. Many U.S. citizens do not carry--or even \b0 \i \ul0 own\b0 \i0 \ul0 --the sort of "papers" that the Arizona legislature expects them to possess at all times. These individuals will be at risk of frequent, drawn-out detention, and the demeaning experience of criminal arrest.
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 A. S.B. 1070 will require U.S. citizens to carry "papers" at all times--or run the risk of criminal detention.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 S.B. 1070 and its copycats will have an unprecedented effect on the lives of U.S. citizens. Section 2(B), the "stop and verify" provision, requires \b \i0 \ul0 [**13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Arizona police to determine the immigration status of any person they stop if "reasonable suspicion" exists to believe the person is "unlawfully present" in the United States. n4 Citizens will therefore have to carry  \b \i0 \ul0 [*5]\b0 \i0 \ul0   their "papers" at all times or face the risk of lengthy detention and false arrest. n5
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n4 Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 11-1051(B).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n5 \b0 \i \ul0 See infra\b0 \i0 \ul0  Part I.B.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Never before have U.S. citizens been subjected to a general requirement that they carry proof of citizenship. Americans have rejected all legislative attempts to create a national identity card. n6 This reflects the long-standing, widely shared belief that having to prove one's citizenship over and over again would unduly impinge upon individual liberty.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n6 G. DAVID GARSON, PUBLIC INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY AND E-GOVERNANCE: MANAGING THE VIRTUAL STATE 171-73 (2006).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**14]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 U.S. citizens in Arizona have already begun to experience the ramifications of "papers please" policing. \b \i0 \ul0 Jim Shee\b0 \i0 \ul0  n7 is a seventy-one-year-old U.S. citizen of Spanish and Chinese ancestry. Despite having lived in Arizona his entire life, he is now being forced to suffer through the indignity of being repeatedly forced to prove his citizenship. On April 6, 2010, Mr. Shee was stopped for no apparent reason and questioned by a Phoenix police officer, who demanded to see his "papers." He was not given a citation. A similar sequence played out again in Yuma a mere ten days later.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n7 Declaration of Jim Shee, \b0 \i \ul0 Friendly House et al. v. Whiting,\b0 \i0 \ul0  No. CV-10-01061-PHX-JWS (D. Ariz. July 9, 2010).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Mr. Shee's experiences indicate the harm that the "stop and verify" provision will inflict on U.S. citizens. In Arizona, the Department of Public Safety makes well over 500,000 stops per year. n8 The vast  \b \i0 \ul0 [*6]\b0 \i0 \ul0   majority of stops are for minor traffic or equipment violations. n9 As in Mr. Shee's case, over ninety-eight \b \i0 \ul0 [**15]\b0 \i0 \ul0   percent do not result in arrest. n10 S.B. 1070 will transform these routine traffic stops into mini-trials where detained citizens bear the burden of proving their status.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n8 UNIV. OF CINCINNATI POLICING INST., TRAFFIC STOP DATA ANALYSIS STUDY: YEAR 3 FINAL REPORT PREPARED FOR THE ARIZONA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY 17 (2009) [hereinafter ARIZ. STOP DATA],
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n9 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 30
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n10 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 49.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Arizona attempts to downplay S.B. 1070's harm to U.S. citizens by promising that individuals stopped by police will be presumed lawfully present so long as they provide a "valid Arizona driver's license, tribal identification, or identification from any unit of government in the United States that requires proof of lawful presence." n11
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n11 Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 11-1051(B).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Although many adult Arizonans possess driver's licenses, a significant \b \i0 \ul0 [**16]\b0 \i0 \ul0   number of U.S. citizens will not have ready access to "proof of lawful presence." Less than half own passports, n12 and as many as seven percent (roughly thirteen million citizens) do not have ready access to naturalization papers or birth certificates. n13
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n12 \b0 \i \ul0 Passport Statistics,\b0 \i0 \ul0  U.S. DEP'T OF STATE, http://travel.state.gov/passport/ppi/stats/stats_890.html (last visited Mar. 26, 2012).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n13 BRENNAN CTR. FOR JUSTICE, CITIZENS WITHOUT PROOF: A SURVEY OF AMERICANS' POSSESSION OF DOCUMENTARY PROOF OF CITIZENSHIP AND PHOTO IDENTIFICATION 2 (2006) (noting that citizens with comparatively low incomes are even less likely to possess documentary proof of citizenship).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 U.S. citizens from states that do not require proof of citizenship in order to obtain licenses will not  \b \i0 \ul0 [*7]\b0 \i0 \ul0   qualify for Section 2(B)'s presumption. n14 As a consequence, Section 2(B) will infringe upon their freedom to travel through Arizona and states with S.B. 1070 copycats. \b \i0 \ul0 Jesus Cuauhtemoc Villa\b0 \i0 \ul0  n15 is a U.S. citizen who will not \b \i0 \ul0 [**17]\b0 \i0 \ul0   qualify for the presumption. Mr. Villa currently attends Arizona State University, but he is a resident of New Mexico, a state which does not require proof of U.S. citizenship to obtain a driver's license. Villa does not own a U.S. passport and therefore cannot drive in Arizona without risking arrest and detention due to his lack of proof of citizenship.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n14 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  ARIZ. PEACE OFFICER STANDARDS & TRAINING BD., PRESUMPTIVE IDENTIFICATIONS (2010), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://agency.azpost.gov/supporting_docs/PresumptiveIdentifications.pdf.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n15 Complaint at 22, \b0 \i \ul0 Friendly House,\b0 \i0 \ul0  No. CV-10-01061-PHX-JWS (D. Ariz. May 17, 2010).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even U.S. citizens who own documents proving citizenship often will not be able to produce them on the spot. This would have been true, for instance, if Mr. Shee had forgotten his driver's license at home. Car passengers, joggers, hikers, and bicyclists can also be stopped, and are not likely to have papers with them. People whose birth certificates constitute their only proof of citizenship \b \i0 \ul0 [**18]\b0 \i0 \ul0   logically store them away in safe, relatively inaccessible places. Out-of-state visitors and college students, for example, may own proof of citizenship, but will not be able to produce these documents.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*8]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 B. S.B 1070 will expose U.S. citizens to detention and the consequences of being erroneously labeled "unlawfully present."\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Citizens stopped in Arizona without the requisite papers will risk being detained and falsely labeled "unlawfully present." n16 Petitioners assume Arizona officers can call the Law Enforcement Support Center ("LESC"), run by Immigration and Customs Enforcement ("ICE"), in order to verify immigration status. n17 This plan is neither as simple nor as effective as Petitioners would have it--especially where citizens are concerned.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n16 Petitioners cite \b0 \i \ul0 Muehler v. Mena,\b0 \i0 \ul0  544 U.S. 93 (2005), for the proposition that local police may ask about immigration status. Pet. Br. at 22, 44. \b0 \i \ul0 Mena,\b0 \i0 \ul0  however, was not a preemption case, and held only that there was no Fourth Amendment violation because the questioning did not extend the time Mena was detained. 544 U.S. at 101. By contrast, Section 2(B) contemplates extending the time of detention by directing that the officer "shall have the person's immigration status determined before the person is released." Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 11-1051(B).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**19]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n17 Pet. Br. at 13.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Petitioners assert that "[r]equesting and receiving information from LESC is quick and can be done during an investigatory stop." n18 On average, however, it takes seventy minutes before someone at the LESC is even available to receive such a request, let alone begin to make the status determination. n19
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n18 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n19 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Declaration of David C. Palmatier, P 8 ("Currently, the average query waits for approximately seventy minutes before a Law Enforcement Specialist is available to work on the request.").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*9]\b0 \i0 \ul0   After waiting the initial seventy minutes, it is unclear how Arizona officers--or for that matter, the LESC--will go about determining whether someone is a citizen. Unlike immigrants, who have registered with the federal government, U.S. citizens are not listed in a central database. n20 A "no match" response could mean either that a person such as Jim Shee is a citizen or that \b \i0 \ul0 [**20]\b0 \i0 \ul0   he entered the country without inspection. n21 Give these complications, status verification can take days to complete. n22 All the while, U.S. citizens will be treated as unwelcome in their own country.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n20 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at P 19.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n21 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at P 12.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n22 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  S. POVERTY LAW CTR., ALABAMA'S SHAME: HB 56 AND THE WAR ON IMMIGRANTS 9-10 (2012) [hereinafter ALABAMA'S SHAME] (profiling Alabama mother wrongfully detained for three days by local authorities until ICE verified her status).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The likelihood that Arizona police will mistake U.S. citizens for unauthorized immigrants is very real. In part, this is because Arizona purports to accomplish on-the-spot what federal authorities have trouble doing with the investment of greater time and resources. Since 2000, thousands of U.S. citizens have been mistaken for aliens and detained or deported. n23 In southern Arizona, between 2006 and  \b \i0 \ul0 [*10]\b0 \i0 \ul0   2008 slightly more than one percent of immigration detainees turned out to be U.S. citizens. n24
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n23 Jacqueline Stevens, \b0 \i \ul0 U.S. Government Unlawfully Detaining and Deporting U.S. Citizens as Aliens,\b0 \i0 \ul0  VA. J. SOC. POL'Y & L. 606, 608(2011).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**21]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n24 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 622. In part to address this problem, last month ICE created a new position to address problems "related to ICE enforcement actions that affect U.S. citizens." \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Andrew Lo-renzen-Strait, \b0 \i \ul0 ICE Announces First-Ever Public Advocate,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Dep't of Homeland Security (Feb. 7, 2012, 8:58 AM), \b0 \i \ul0 http://blog.dhs.gov/2012/02/ice-announces-first-ever-public.html\b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 .\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Citizens who acquired or derived their citizenship are two examples of people who will be at special risk for being mistakenly labeled "unlawfully present." Acquired U.S. citizenship is conveyed to individuals born outside of the United States to U.S. citizen parents. n25 Because they are citizens at birth, these individuals will not appear in the LESC's database. n26 As a matter of law, minor LPRs derive U.S. citizenship when at least one of their parents naturalizes. n27 Derived citizens may apply for a Certificate of Citizenship--at a cost of $ 600--but they otherwise will not have documents proving their citizenship. n28 And since their citizenship is conveyed only as a matter of law, they will appear in the LESC database \b \i0 \ul0 [**22]\b0 \i0 \ul0   as LPRs.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n25 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 U.S.C. \'a7 1401(c)-(e).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n26 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Palmatier Decl. at P 19.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n27 See 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1431.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n28 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  DEPT. OF HOMELAND SEC, U.S. CITIZENSHIP & IMMIGRATION SERVS. INSTRUCTIONS FOR FORM N-600, APPLICATION FOR CERTIFICATE OF CITIZENSHIP, \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.uscis.gov/files/form/n-600instr.pdf.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Given these complications, even federal immigration authorities have mistaken derivative citizens  \b \i0 \ul0 [*11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   for non-citizens. For example, \b \i0 \ul0 George Ibarra\b0 \i0 \ul0  n29 is a fourth-generation U.S. citizen with grand and greatgrand parents born in Arizona and California. He was born in the border town of Nogales, Mexico, but has lived in Arizona since infancy. He derived citizenship through his U.S. citizen mother. A veteran wounded during the first Gulf War, today Mr. Ibarra suffers from PTSD. He has been mistaken for a noncitizen and erroneously deported on two separate occasions. n30
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n29 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Jacqueline Stevens, \b0 \i \ul0 DHS Releases U.S. Citizen George Ibarra From Eloy Detention Center,\b0 \i0 \ul0  STATES WITHOUT NATIONS (MAY 4, 2011, 2:01 PM), http://stateswithoutnations.blogspot.com/ 2011/05/dhs-release-us-citizen-george-ibarra.html.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**23]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n30 Mr. Ibarra's story also points to the reality that citizens with mental disabilities are particularly vulnerable to such mistakes. \b0 \i \ul0 See Written Testimony of Kara Hartzler, Problems with ICE Interrogation, Detention, and Removal Procedures: Hearing Before the Subcomm. on Immigration, Citizenship, Refugees, Border Security and Int'l Law of the H. Comm. on the Judiciary,\b0 \i0 \ul0  110th Cong. 2 (2008) \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://judiciary.house.gov/hearings/printers/110th/40742.pdf.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even with all of its resources, expertise, and access to data, federal authorities still err in deter-mining--over the course of weeks and months--who is a citizen. Yet Arizona, without any of these advantages, purports to have its officers sort out this question on the spot during the course of "any lawful contact made by a law enforcement official."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 C. Citizens of color will disproportionately bear the burden of "papers please" policing.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Mr. Shee's story reflects the reality that citizens of certain ethnic and racial backgrounds have more frequent contact with law enforcement. Under S.B. 1070, these citizens \b \i0 \ul0 [**24]\b0 \i0 \ul0   will likely have to prove their status many times each year. This "aggregation of thousands upon thousands of petty indignities has a substantial impact on freedom" n31--and undermines the status of all citizens of color who find themselves in Arizona.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n31 \b0 \i \ul0 Maryland v. Wilson,\b0 \i0 \ul0  519 U.S. 408, 419 (1997) (Stevens, J., dissenting) (noting "potential daily burden on thousands of innocent citizens" resulting from police officers ordering passengers out of cars during routine traffic stops); see \b0 \i \ul0 also \b0 \i0 \ul0 \b0 \i \ul0 id.\b0 \i0 \ul0  at 423 (Kennedy, J., dissenting) (joining Justice Stevens' dissent and warning against "risk of arbitrary control by the police").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 People of color in Arizona are far more likely to be stopped by police than are their white counterparts. In Maricopa County--by far Arizona's largest--Latino drivers are over four times more likely to be stopped than similarly situated non-Latino drivers. n32 Minorities stopped in Arizona are also more likely than whites to be searched, and are detained \b \i0 \ul0 [**25]\b0 \i0 \ul0   for longer periods of time despite the fact that they are less likely to be found in possession of contraband. n33  \b \i0 \ul0 [*13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Section 2(B) will exacerbate these patterns, subjecting citizens of color to yet greater scrutiny and detention.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n32 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Letter from Thomas E. Perez, Ass. Att'y Gen., U.S. Dept. of Justice, Civil Rights Div., to Bill Montgomery, Att'y Maricopa Cnty. (Dec. 15, 2011), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.justice.gov/crtyabout/spl/documents/mcso_findletter_12-15-11.pdf.
\par \fs20 \pard 
