\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 II. S.B. 1070 MISAPPREHENDS THE FEDERAL IMMIGRATION SCHEME, INSTITUTING STATE CRIMINAL CONSEQUENCES THAT CONTRAVENE CONGRESSIONAL POLICY.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Even if the citizenship/alienage issue described in Part I were readily resolvable, the question of whether a non-citizen is "lawfully present" is a nuanced legal inquiry, not an on-the-spot factual determination. This section describes non-citizens who will be harmed by the Arizona Legislature's fundamental misapprehension of the federal immigration scheme. These individuals will be exposed to state criminal consequences, in conflict with congressional policy.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*14]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 A. Section 3 will criminalize failure to register by individuals with no way to register under the federal scheme.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Section 3 of S.B. 1070--which criminalizes failure to register for and carry registration documents n36--epitomizes the Arizona Legislature's misapprehension of federal immigration law. Petitioners claim that this provision represents a "parallel" enforcement of federal registration requirements, "overlap \b \i0 \ul0 [**27]\b0 \i0 \ul0   [ping] precisely with federal direction in both its substantive elements and its penalty." n37 In reality, Section 3 departs dramatically from longstanding federal registration policy.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n36 Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 13-1509(A).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n37 Pet. Br. at 51. \b0 \i \ul0 See also\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief of State Senator Russell Pearce as \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Curiae In Support Of Petitioners at 10 [hereinafter Pearce \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief] ("Section 3 simply codifies federal law."); Brief of Joseph M. Arpaio, Maricopa County Sheriff as \b0 \i \ul0 Amici Curiae\b0 \i0 \ul0  in Support of Petitioner at 4 [hereinafter Arpaio \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief] ("Section 3 essentially adopts federal law and provides for its enforcement under Arizona law."); Statement of Governor Jan Brewer on Signing S.B. 1070 (Apr. 23, 2010) ("[T]he new state misdemeanor crime of willful failure to complete or carry an alien registration document is adopted, verbatim, from the same offense found in [sic] federal statute."), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.p2012.org/issues/brewer042310sp.html.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In stating that the \b \i0 \ul0 [**28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   "difference between Section 3 and the federal statutes is that Section 3 has no application at all to persons authorized to be in the United States," n38 Petitioners reveal their crucial misunderstanding: Section 3 refers to a statute, the implementing regulations for which are almost entirely  \b \i0 \ul0 [*15]\b0 \i0 \ul0   addressed to persons \b0 \i \ul0 authorized\b0 \i0 \ul0  to be in the United States. n39
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n38 Pet. Br. at 17.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n39 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 C.F.R. \'a7 264.1(b) (listing forms of evidence of registration, none of which are available to immigrants who entered without inspection).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 While the Alien Registration Act of 1940 states that "it shall be the duty of every alien . . . to apply for registration," n40 for over fifty years the federal registration scheme has excluded entrants without inspection ("EWIs") from its ambit. n41 Even the post-9-11 "special registration" imposed by the Attorney General on particular groups n42 did not cover EWIs. n43
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n40 Sec. 31(a), Ch. 439, 54 Stat. 670, 673-74 (1940) (codified at 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1302(a)).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**29]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n41 \b0 \i \ul0 See, e.g.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Alien Registration, 25 Fed. Reg. 7180 (July 29. 1960) (listing prescribed federal registration forms, none of which apply to EWIs).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n42 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 U.S.C. \'a7 1303. The Attorney General exercised this power in a series of rules promulgated following the attacks of September 11, but none of the promulgated rules purported to apply to EWIs. \b0 \i \ul0 See, e.g.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  Registration of Certain Nonimmigrant Aliens from Designated Countries, 67 Fed. Reg. 67766 (Nov. 6, 2002) (notice) (subjecting aliens from Iran, Iraq, Libya, Sudan, and Syria to special registration).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n43 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  IMMIGRATION AND NATURALIZATION SERVS., SPECIAL CALL-IN REGISTRATION PROCEDURES 4 (2002), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.deans.medsch.ucla.edu/visa/Official%20INS%20Special%20Registration%20Information%20Sheet.pdf (explaining that registration requirements "apply only to aliens who have been inspected by an Immigration officer").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Contrary to this longstanding federal interpretation, Arizona ignores federal regulations and reinterprets vestigial language in 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1302(a) \b \i0 \ul0 [**30]\b0 \i0 \ul0   as requiring EWIs to register. This leads to the bizarre result of punishing "failure to register" by immigrants  \b \i0 \ul0 [*16]\b0 \i0 \ul0   who have no way to register under the federal scheme.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Since EWIs will have no way to comply with this phantom registration requirement, Section 3 will \b0 \i \ul0 de facto\b0 \i0 \ul0  criminalize their presence in this country. This is in direct conflict with Congress's decision not to criminalize mere presence. All legislative proposals to criminalize mere presence have failed. Indeed, Congress considered and rejected criminalizing "unlawful presence" a few short years before the Arizona Legislature moved to embrace it. n44
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n44 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  H.R. 4437, 105th Cong. \'a7 203 (2005) (imposing misdemeanor-level penalties on any alien "present in the United States in violation of the immigration laws").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Most EWIs, while potentially removable, are simply not subject to criminal penalties under the federal scheme. Although illegal entry is a misdemeanor punishable under 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1325(a), it is governed \b \i0 \ul0 [**31]\b0 \i0 \ul0   by the federal five-year statute of limitations. n45 Over ninety percent of unauthorized immigrants entered before 2005 and are therefore not chargeable under this provision of the federal code. n46 In contrast, Section 3 will criminalize unlawful presence on an ongoing basis. n47
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n45 18 U.S.C. \'a7 3282(a).
