\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 C. Section 6 will expose Lawful Permanent Residents, and other authorized immigrants, to wrongful arrest and detention.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Section 6 of S.B. 1070 authorizes an Arizona officer, without a warrant, to "arrest a person \b \i0 \ul0 [**42]\b0 \i0 \ul0   if the officer has probable cause to believe . . . [t]he person to be arrested has committed any public offense that makes the person removable from the United States." n71 Arizona thus grants \b0 \i \ul0 local\b0 \i0 \ul0  officers substantially more power than Congress has given even \b0 \i \ul0 federal\b0 \i0 \ul0  immigration officers. n72 This will expose LPRs and other authorized immigrants with past convictions to wrongful arrest and criminal detention.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n71 Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 13-3883.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n72 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1357(a)(4) (authorizing federal officers to make warrantless arrests only "if there is likelihood of the person escaping before a warrant can be obtained"); 8 C.F.R. \'a7 287.5 (same).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Arizona assumes that removability based on past convictions is a simple determination that police can make on the spot. In reality, this is a legal determination  \b \i0 \ul0 [*24]\b0 \i0 \ul0   that requires knowledge of a suspect's immigration status, current case law, and the nature of the past convictions. For this reason, the federal \b \i0 \ul0 [**43]\b0 \i0 \ul0   scheme contemplates careful deliberation by expert officials prior to the issuance of a "Notice to Appear" before an immigration judge. n73 And, to prevent error, the federal scheme prohibits federal officers from making warrantless arrests unless the suspect presents a flight risk. n74
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n73 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Memorandum from John P. Torres, Acting Dir. ICE, Office of Detention and Removal to ICE Field Officers on the Detention and Deportation Officer's Field Manual \'a7 11.3 (Mar. 27, 2006), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.legalactioncenter.org/sites/default/files/docs/lac/ICE-DetentionDeportation-OfricerFieldManual.pdf.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n74 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 U.S.C. \'a7 1357(a)(4); 8 C.F.R. \'a7 287.5.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Local police are bound to make repeated mistakes given their lack of immigration law expertise, and the inherent impossibility of making these determinations on the spot. As a result, LPRs and other lawfully present immigrants with criminal records will live in constant fear of arrest by Arizona police--even \b \i0 \ul0 [**44]\b0 \i0 \ul0   if their crimes do not subject them to immigration consequences. n75
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n75 Russell Pearce. the self-described "author of, and driving force behind" S.B. 1070, claims that Section 6's warrantless arrest authority applies only where a suspect has "willfully failed or refused to depart after having been ordered to be removed by a federal immigration judge." Pearce \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief, \b0 \i \ul0 supra\b0 \i0 \ul0  note 38, at 1, 13. The statute's language does not admit of this narrow interpretation and the Court should not credit Mr. Pearce's \b0 \i \ul0 post facto\b0 \i0 \ul0  attempt to rewrite S.B. 1070.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Petitions argued below that Section 6 should be construed "so as to require officers to confirm with federal authorities that an alien has committed a  \b \i0 \ul0 [*25]\b0 \i0 \ul0   public offense that makes the alien removable before making a warrantless arrest." n76 Even if the provision were so interpreted, it would still expand the power of state authorities to make immigration arrests far beyond the scope sanctioned by Congress. Whereas 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1252c \b \i0 \ul0 [**45]\b0 \i0 \ul0   authorizes state and local law enforcement officials to arrest certain "alien[s] . . . previously . . . convicted of a \b0 \i \ul0 felony\b0 \i0 \ul0 " n77 Section 6 allows for arrests where the individual has committed \b0 \i \ul0 "any public offense\b0 \i0 \ul0  that makes the person removable." n78
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n76 Appellants' Opening Brief at 54, \b0 \i \ul0 United States u. Ariz.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  641 F.3d 339 (9th Cir. 2011) (No. 10-16645).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n77 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  8 U.S.C. \'a7 1252c(a)(2) (emphasis added).
