\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 III. REAL-WORLD EVIDENCE BELIES PETITIONERS' THEORETICAL ARGUMENT THAT S.B. 1070 CAN BE IMPLEMENTED IN A MANNER CONSISTENT WITH THE CONSTITUTION.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Petitioners and their \b0 \i \ul0 amici\b0 \i0 \ul0  invite the Court to identify some narrow reading of S.B. 1070 in the hope that the enactment might survive this facial challenge. The Court should not strain to identify such a legal fiction. The plain language of the statute, the stated understandings of its would-be enforcers, and the real-world experience of \b \i0 \ul0 [**46]\b0 \i0 \ul0   people of color in Arizona and the other copycat states all serve to refute Petitioners' claim that S.B. 1070 can be implemented in a manner consistent with the Constitution. n79
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n79 While 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1357(g)(10)(B) allows the Attorney General, in the absence of formal agreements, to involve interested states in cooperative immigration-related efforts, Petitioners read this provision as an invitation for states to invent immigration enforcement schemes that are independent of the federal scheme. Pet. Br. at 32. Petitioner's interpretation of that provision reads out the "co-" in the word "cooperate." This unilateral approach to cooperation is at odds with the federal scheme.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360  \b \i0 \ul0 [*26]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 A. Arizona's track record lays bare the hollowness of Petitioners' contention that S.B. 1070 can be carried out in a constitutional manner.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Arizona's failure to safeguard civil rights and its unwillingness to respect federal control over immigration enforcement both militate toward upholding the injunction.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**47]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Maricopa County, home to over half of Arizona's residents, n80 joined the 287(g) program in 2007. n81 The program allows certain state and local law enforcement officers to be trained by ICE to perform immigration enforcement activities pursuant to a formal contract with the federal government that requires, \b0 \i \ul0 inter alia,\b0 \i0 \ul0  that they function under the control and supervision of federal authorities. n82 In 2009 and again last year, the federal government was forced to drastically curtail Maricopa County's 287(g) authorization. n83 According to the DOJ, the  \b \i0 \ul0 [*27]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Maricopa County Sheriff's Office ("MCSO") systematically engaged in "racial profiling of Latinos" through unlawful stops, arrests, and detentions. n84
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n80 Arpaio \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief, \b0 \i \ul0 supra\b0 \i0 \ul0  note 38, at 2.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n81 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Memorandum of Agreement Between ICE and Maricopa County, Feb. 24, 2007, \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.aclu.org/files/pdfs/immigrants/maricopa_moa_20070207.pdf.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n82 8 U.S.C. \'a7 1357(g)(1)-(9).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n83 Ray Stern, \b0 \i \ul0 Feds Pull 287(g) Authority From Maricopa County Jails Because of Civil Rights Violations,\b0 \i0 \ul0  PHOENIX NEW TIMES (Dec. 15 2011, 1:00 PM), http://blogs.phoenixnewtimes.com/valleyfever/ 2011/12/feds_pull_287g_authority_from.php.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**48]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n84 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Letter from Thomas E. Perez, Ass. Att'y Gen., U.S. Dept. of Justice, Civil Rights Div., to Bill Montgomery, Att'y Maricopa Cnty. (Dec. 15, 2011), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/spl/documents/mcso_findletter_12-15-11.pdf.
