\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This officially sanctioned racial profiling has resulted in rampant harassment of U.S. citizens and LPRs. \b \i0 \ul0 Julio\b0 \i0 \ul0  Cesar \b \i0 \ul0 Mora,\b0 \i0 \ul0  n85 born in Avondale, Arizona, is a U.S. citizen of Mexican ancestry. On February 11, 2009, Mr. Mora and his then sixty-six-yearold father (an LPR who had lived in the United States for thirty years) were on their way to work. Just yards from their destination, they were surrounded by two MCSO vehicles, and ordered out of their pick-up truck. They were frisked, handcuffed, and eventually taken to Mr. Mora's workplace--the site of an MCSO immigration raid. Along with over 100 others, they were corralled by masked officers carrying semi-automatic rifles. Mr. Mora is still astounded by the treatment he received. As he explains, "[m]aybe it was because of the Campesina radio station sticker on our bumper or . . .  \b \i0 \ul0 [**49]\b0 \i0 \ul0   because my  \b \i0 \ul0 [*28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   dad was wearing his Mexican tejana [hat] and they thought we were illegal. But they never bothered to ask us."
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n85 \b0 \i \ul0 See Testimony of Julio Cesar Mora, Pub. Safety & Civil Rights Implications of State and Local Enforcement of Immigration Laws: Hearing Before the Subcomm. on Immigration, Citizenship, Refugees, Border Security and Int'l Law and the Subcomm. on the Const., Civil Rights, & Civil Liberties of the H. Comm. on the Judiciary,\b0 \i0 \ul0  111th Cong. 11 (2009), \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://judiciary.house.gov/hearings/printers/111th/111-19_48439.pdf.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 MCSO has brazenly undermined federal control over immigration enforcement. Asked why his office refused to cooperate with an investigation of the county's "discriminatory practices," Sheriff Joseph Arpaio explained: "Do you think I'm going to report to the federal government? I don't report to them." n86 Yet Mr. Arpaio submits an \b0 \i \ul0 amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  brief in this case claiming he is ready to cooperate with federal immigration enforcement. n87
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n86 \b0 \i \ul0 Immigration, Outsourced,\b0 \i0 \ul0  N.Y. TIMES, Apr. 9, 2008, at A24.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**50]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n87 Arpaio \b0 \i \ul0 Amicus\b0 \i0 \ul0  Brief at 14 ("The Court should assume that Arizona law enforcement officials will comply with federal law in executing Section 2(B).").
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Federal control of the 287(g) program allowed DOJ to "pull the plug" on MCSO in light of its egregious misconduct. Lifting the injunction not only would restore MCSO's power; it also would severely limit the federal government's future ability to supervise MCSO's immigration enforcement activities. Worse still, Arizona would be given license to run a rival immigration regime that departs dramatically from federal design.
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 B. Laws like S.B. 1070 embolden individuals to commit private acts of racial discrimination.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Laws like S.B. 1070 signal to members of the public that some of their neighbors, customers, and employees are henceforth "illegal." Following the example  \b \i0 \ul0 [*29]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of their state governments, private actors have begun treating people with brown skin or accents as second-class citizens. In Alabama, for example, H.B. 56 has emboldened acts of blatant racism toward anyone perceived as foreign. The view from the ground is frightening.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**51]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Carmen Gonzalez\b0 \i0 \ul0  n88 is a U.S. citizen and the mother of two U.S. citizen children. Born in Texas, she has lived in Foley, Alabama for most of her life. In December of 2011, she was greeted by a piece of paper on the floor of her vehicle that read: "Go Back to Mexico." When her son asked if his family was going to Mexico, Ms. Gonzalez was forced to explain, "You're allowed to be here . . . You're supposed to be here."
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n88 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  ALABAMA'S SHAME, \b0 \i \ul0 supra\b0 \i0 \ul0  note 17, at 7.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 N.L., n89 originally from Mexico, resides in Shelby, Alabama, with her husband and two U.S. citizen daughters. On a recent afternoon at a lunch buffet, her deaf seven-year-old daughter crossed in front of a white man whom she did not hear coming, causing him to bobble his plate. Furious, the man intentionally poured barbecue sauce on top of the young girl. He yelled anti-immigrant epithets at her while she struggled to her feet. Hurt and feeling helpless to confront the man, the family quickly cleared the table, paid, and left the restaurant.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**52]\b0 \i0 \ul0   
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n89 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Letter from Tom Fritzsche, Esq. & Samuel Brooke, Esq., S. Poverty Law Ctr., to Nancy Morawetz, Supervising Att'y, Washington Sq. Legal Servs. (Mar. 23, 2012) (on file with Washington Sq. Legal Servs.).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 W.H., n90 originally from Mexico, resides in Birmingham, Alabama. In October, after protecting  \b \i0 \ul0 [*30]\b0 \i0 \ul0   his wife and three-year-old U.S. citizen son from an attack by a neighbor's pitbull, he asked the neighbor to be more careful with the dog. The neighbor responded by hurling racial insults at him and threatening to "have him deported" if he made a fuss about the dog.
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n90 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Hortensia n91 of Decatur, Alabama performed three days of landscaping work around the home of her employer. When she went to collect her pay, she was met with the barrel of a gun, and told she "couldn't do anything" because she did not have "papers.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**53]\b0 \i0 \ul0   "
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n91 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  ALABAMA'S SHAME, \b0 \i \ul0 supra\b0 \i0 \ul0  note 17, at 13-14.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Hortensia's story illustrates one reason why Congress rejected the criminalization of work performed by unauthorized immigrants: protection of a "fair day's pay for a fair day's work." See, \b0 \i \ul0 e.g.,\b0 \i0 \ul0  President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, \b0 \i \ul0 Public Papers,\b0 \i0 \ul0  VI (May 24, 1937). Cognizant of this congressional objective, the lower courts were correct to enjoin Section 5(C).
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As these stories illustrate, the particulars of S.B. 1070 and its copycats are lost on many laypersons. They simply view these state immigration laws as giving them license to treat people with brown skin or accents as second-class citizens.
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi0 C. Laws like S.B. 1070 divide our nation into regions where people of color can freely live and travel--and regions where they cannot.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The backdrop for the passage of S.B. 1070 is the reality of shifting demographics in Arizona and the nation as whole. The United States has rapidly become a diverse nation, welcoming people of all races  \b \i0 \ul0 [*31]\b0 \i0 \ul0    \b \i0 \ul0 [**54]\b0 \i0 \ul0   and countries of origin. Racial and ethnic minorities accounted for 91.7% of the nation's growth during the 2000-2010 decade. The growth rates of the Latino population have been 43%, 53% and 58%, for the past three decades, respectively. As of 2010, there were 50.5 million Latino residents of the United States--16.3% of the total population. This includes 4.6 million Latinos born in Puerto Rico, who are U.S. citizens by birth. n92 Nationwide, 74% of all Latinos are U.S. citizens by birth or naturalization. n93 Of the 31,674,000 residents of Mexican ancestry in the United States, 20.3 million (64.1%) are citizens born in this country and 2.6 million (8.2%) are naturalized citizens. n94 Meanwhile, only one-third of Latinos between the ages of sixteen and twenty-five were born abroad. n95
\par \pard 
