\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Arizona exemplifies these trends. More than one in four Arizonans is Latino. For youths between the ages sixteen and twenty-five, the figure is over one in three. n96 As of 2009, close to 1.3 million Latinos  \b \i0 \ul0 [*32]\b0 \i0 \ul0   lived in the Phoenix Metropolitan Area alone; n97 over two-thirds of them were born here as U.S. citizens. n98
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n96 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n97 \b0 \i \ul0 Latinos by Geography,\b0 \i0 \ul0  PEW HISPANIC CTR. (Mar. 16, 2012), http://www.pewhispanic.org/2012/03/16/latinos-by-geography (last visited Mar. 26, 2012).
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n98 \b0 \i \ul0 Id.\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 S.B. 1070 and its copycats subject new Americans--and all people of color--to constant scrutiny about their immigration status. Many immigrants and people of color have packed up and left their \b \i0 \ul0 [**56]\b0 \i0 \ul0   home states. In Arizona, both legally present and undocumented, have begun leaving the state in droves." n99 In Alabama, the exodus of Latinos began just hours after H.B. 56 passed, with frightened families leaving behind fully furnished mobile homes in order to take refuge in other states. n100
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n99 Alan Gomez, \b0 \i \ul0 Hispanics Flee Arizona Ahead of Immigration Law,\b0 \i0 \ul0  USA TODAY, June, 9, 2010, at A1.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n100 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Campbell Roberson, \b0 \i \ul0 After Ruling, Hispanics Flee an Alabama Town,\b0 \i0 \ul0  N.Y. Times, Oct. 3, 2011 at A1.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Meanwhile, immigrants and other people of color who remain in states like Arizona and Alabama have been deterred from seeking basic public services. Following the passage of Alabama's law, hundreds of fearful parents pulled their children out of public schools. n101 The Alabama Department of Public Health is concerned that H.B. 56 is keeping people from seeking medical care, thereby increasing the  \b \i0 \ul0 [*33]\b0 \i0 \ul0   risk of illnesses across the state. n102 Immigrants of faith have also been forced into the shadows.  \b \i0 \ul0 [**57]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Latinos have grown reluctant to attend Spanish-language worship or access services such as English classes. In this climate, congregations and ministries have been forced to shut down. n103
\par \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n101 In Montgomery County, more than 200 Latino students were absent the morning after learning that the law would go into effect. \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Jay Reeves, \b0 \i \ul0 Hispanic Students Vanish From Alabama Schools,\b0 \i0 \ul0  ASSOCIATED PRESS, Sept. 30, 2011, \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/44734906/ns/us_news-life/t/hispanic-students-vanish-alabama-schools/#.T3ABYmEged8.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n102 \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Jay Reeves, \b0 \i \ul0 Alabama Immigration Law Sparking Public Health Worries,\b0 \i0 \ul0  ASSOCIATED PRESS, Oct. 28, 2011, \b0 \i \ul0 available at\b0 \i0 \ul0  http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/45081790/ns/health/t/ala-immigration-lawsparking-public-health-worries. This is particularly problematic for sufferers of HIV/AIDS, who will be deterred from accessing testing and lifesaving medical treatment.
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n103 This problem is compounded by the transportation problems presented by Alabama's "harboring and transport" provision. \b0 \i \ul0 See\b0 \i0 \ul0  Beason-Hammon Alabama Taxpayer and Citizen Protection Act, 2011 Alabama Laws Act 2011-535 (H.B. 56), \'a7 13(a)(1) (codified at Ala. Code \'a7 31-13-13(a)(1)) ("It shall be unlawful for a person to . . . . [c]onceal, harbor, or shield or attempt to conceal, harbor, or shield or conspire to conceal, harbor, or shield an alien from detection in any place in this state . . . . "). Although S.B. 1070 shares this feature, \b0 \i \ul0 see\b0 \i0 \ul0  Ariz. Rev. Stat. Ann. \'a7 13-2929(A)(2)-(3), it is not before the Court.
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  
\par \fs20 \pard 
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [**58]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The marginalization of people of color comes as no surprise to the drafters of S.B. 1070 and its copycats. State-level "attrition through enforcement" laws are designed to divide our nation between those regions where people of all ethnicities can freely travel, live and work--and those where they cannot.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*34]\b0 \i0 \ul0   \b \i0 \ul0 CONCLUSION\b0 \i0 \ul0 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 For these reasons, the decision of the Court of Appeals should be affirmed.
